{{Infobox language family |name=Central Maluku |region=[[Maluku Islands]] (Indonesia) |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] (MP) |fam3=[[Central–Eastern Malayo-Polynesian languages|Central–Eastern MP]] |child1=Teor-Kur |child2=West |child3=East |glotto=cent2254 |glottorefname=Central Maluku }}
The '''Central Maluku languages''' are a putative group of fifty [[Austronesian languages]] (geographically [[Central–Eastern Malayo-Polynesian languages]]) spoken principally on the [[Seram]], [[Buru]], [[Ambon Island|Ambon]], [[Kei Islands|Kei]], and the [[Sula Islands]]. None of the languages have as many as fifty thousand speakers, and several are extinct.
==Classification== The traditional components of Central Maluku are the [[Sula languages|Sula]], [[Buru languages|Buru]], and [[East Central Maluku languages]], plus the [[Ambelau language|Ambelau]] isolate.
===Collins (1983)=== The following classification of the Central Maluku languages below is from Collins (1983:20, 22) and (1986).<ref>Collins, James T. (1983). [https://dx.doi.org/10.15144/PL-D47 ''The Historical Relationships of the Languages of Central Maluku, Indonesia.''] Canberra: Pacific Linguistics.</ref><ref>Collins, J.T. (1986). [https://dx.doi.org/10.15144/PL-C94.123 "Eastern Seram: a subgrouping argument".] In Geraghty, P., Carrington, L. and Wurm, S.A. eds, ''FOCAL II: Papers from the Fourth International Conference on Austronesian Linguistics.'' C-94:123-146. Pacific Linguistics, The Australian National University.</ref>
*[[Teor-Kur language|Teor-Kur]] *West Central Maluku **[[Ambelau language|Ambelau]] **[[Sula–Buru languages|Buru–Sula–Taliabo]] ***'''Buru''': [[Buru language|Buru]], [[Lisela language|Lisela]], [[Palumata language|Palumata]] (extinct), [[Moksela language|Moksela]] (extinct) ***'''Sula''': [[Sula language|Sula]], [[Mangole language|Mangole]] ***[[Taliabo language|Taliabo]] (Kadai, Padang/Samala, Mananga, Mangei/Soboyo)
*East Central Maluku (around [[Seram]] and [[Aru Islands|Aru]]) **Banda–Geser ***[[Banda language (Maluku)|Banda]] ***Geser: [[Bati language (Indonesia)|Bati]], [[Geser language|Geser]], [[Watubela language|Watubela]] **East Seram ***[[Bobot language|Bobot]]–[[Masiwang language|Masiwang]] ***Setic: [[Hoti language|Hoti]], [[Benggoi language|Benggoi]], [[Salas language|Salas]], [[Liana-Seti language|Liana-Seti]] **[[Nunusaku languages|Nunusaku]] ***''[[Kayeli language|Kayeli]]'' ***Patakai–Manusela ****[[Nuaulu language|Nuaulu]] ****[[Huaulu language|Huaulu]], [[Manusela language|Manusela]] ***Three Rivers ****[[Wemale language|Wemale]] ****'''Amalumute''' *****[[Yalahatan language|Yalahatan]] *****Northwest Seram: [[Hulung language|Hulung]], [[Saleman language|Saleman]], [[Loun language|Loun]], Ulat Inai ([[Alune language|Alune]], [[Naka'ela language|Naka'ela]]), [[Lisabata-Nuniali language|Lisabata-Nuniali]] ***[[Piru Bay languages]] (20 languages)
