{{Infobox occupation | name = Daigou | synonyms = | pronounce = | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | official_names = Daigou, Overseas personal shopper<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-43259904|title=How to become a professional shopper|first=Pamela|last=Parker|date=16 March 2018|publisher=[[BBC.com]]}}</ref>, Professional shopper<ref name="auto"/> | type = Profession | activity_sector = [[Retail]] | competencies = | formation = | employment_field = Self-employed | related_occupation = [[Personal shopper]] }} '''Daigou''' ([[Mandarin Chinese|Chinese]]: 代购 dàigòu ({{IPAc-en|lang|pron|ˈ|d|aɪ|ˈ|g|oʊ}}); also 海外代购 hǎiwài dàigòu)<ref name="Katie Hunt">{{cite news| last=Hunt| first=Katie| url= http://www.cnn.com/2014/08/19/world/asia/china-personal-shoppers/| title=Shoppers or smugglers? China cracks down on 'daigou' boom| publisher=[[CNN]]| date=August 19, 2014| accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref>, '''Overseas personal shopper'''<ref name="auto"/> is a channel of commerce in which a person outside of [[China]] purchases commodities (mainly [[luxury goods]] but also groceries) for a customer in [[mainland China]],<ref name="auto"/><ref name="Chitrakorn2014">{{cite web |last=Chitrakorn |first=Kati |date=9 April 2014 |title=‘Daigou’ Agents Help Chinese Get Luxury Goods for Less |url= http://www.businessoffashion.com/2014/04/daigou-agents-help-chinese-consumers-get-luxury-goods-less.html |work= [[businessoffashion.com]] |access-date=28 October 2016 }}</ref> since prices for luxury goods can be 30 to 40 percent higher in China than abroad.<ref name="Menendez">{{cite web |last1=Menendez |first1=Enrique |title=Missed Opportunity: China’s Neglected Domestic Travellers | url= http://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/global-currents/the-missed-opportunity-chinas-neglected-internal-travellers |website=businessoffashion.com |accessdate=28 October 2016 |date=February 18, 2016}}</ref> The phrase means "buying on behalf of".<ref name="Owens">{{cite web |last1=Owens |first1=Susan |title=FROM DAIGOU TO DIGITAL: LUXURY EXECUTIVES WEIGH IN ON BIGGEST CHINA CHALLENGES |url= https://jingdaily.com/from-daigou-to-digital-luxury-executives-weigh-in-on-biggest-china-challenges/ |website=Jing Daily (精日传媒) |accessdate=28 October 2016 |date=July 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Lee">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Terence |title=Daigou, a novel e-commerce business model, is an intriguing Chinese export |url= http://www.techinasia.com/daigou-sites-becoming-popular/ |website=businessoffashion.com |accessdate=October 28, 2016 |date=November 16, 2012}}</ref> ''Daigou'' sales across sectors total $15 billion annually.<ref name="Buchwald">{{cite web |last1=Buchwald |first1=Brian |last2=Neckes |first2=Joshua |title=Op-Ed {{!}} Alibaba’s Catch-22 |url= http://www.businessoffashion.com/2014/08/op-ed-alibabas-catch-22.html |website=businessoffashion.com |accessdate=28 October 2016 |date=August 15, 2014}}</ref> In 2014 the value of the ''daigou'' business just in luxury goods increased from [[Renminbi|CN¥]]55 billion to CN¥75 billion [[RMB|yuan]] (USD $8.8 billion to $12 billion).<ref name="Chitrakorn2016">{{cite web |last1=Chitrakorn |first1=Kati |title=Can China End the Illicit ‘Daigou’ Trade? |url= http://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/global-currents/can-china-put-an-end-to-the-illicit-daigou-trade |website=businessoffashion.com |accessdate=October 28, 2016 |date=February 5, 2016}}</ref>
''Daigou'' purchases are often from luxury brand boutiques in major fashion cities like [[Paris]], [[London]], [[New York City]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Tokyo]] and [[Seoul]]. Some ''daigou'' operators use [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]] and [[WeChat]] to communicate with their clients.<ref name="Zhu">{{cite news| last= Zhu| first= Julie| url= http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/28e6cec4-993e-11e3-b3a2-00144feab7de.html| title= Online agents cut luxury bills for Chinese buyers |publisher=[[Financial Times]]| date=February 23, 2014| accessdate= 2014-08-17}}</ref> The large demand for ''daigou'' service is due to concern over unsafe products, especially food safety problems,<ref name=Baidu>{{cite web |title=中国食品安全问题现状、原因及对策 中国食品安全现状 |url= http://wenku.baidu.com/link?url=L85WJHhOF1h3l3QJfnWAxi09-ZEoovP7xHuKM3Bsqs8wVZPMoVFJSm4XionQIxBwFkLbx9xvHX7_FElf8XMkwomA8CJdHHVH6i5AlbG32Rq |website=Baidu |language=Chinese |date=August 26, 2013 |trans-title=The phenomenon, reasons and solutions of food safety problems in China}}</ref> and China's high [[import tariff]]s on luxury goods.<ref name="Zhu" /> Some ''daigou'' service providers intentionally sell counterfeit [[made-in-China]] products that have been altered to appear purchased abroad.<ref name="Shuan Sim">{{cite news | last= Sim | first= Shuan | url= http://jingdaily.com/chinas-sketchy-daigou-luxury-market-is-a-hotbed-for-fakes/ | title= China’s Sketchy ‘Daigou’ Luxury Market Is A Hotbed For Fakes | publisher= jingdaily.com | date= April 8, 2014 | accessdate= August 29, 2014 }}</ref> A 2015 survey of Chinese online luxury shoppers found that 35% have used ''daigou'' to purchase luxury goods online, while only 7% used the website of the brand they are buying, or think they are buying.<ref name="Solca">{{cite web |last1=Solca |first1=Luca |title=Digital China Leaving Ostrich Brands Behind| url= http://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/opinion/digital-china-leaving-ostrich-brands-behind| website=businessoffashion.com |accessdate=28 October 2016 |date=16 April 2015}}</ref> Approximately 80% of Chinese luxury purchases are made abroad.<ref name="Denis-Wendlandt">{{cite web |last1=Denis |first1=Pascale |last2=Wendlandt |first2=Astrid |editor-last=Holmes |editor-first=David |title=Luxury Market Growth Will Hit Low Point in 2016, Forecasts Bain |url= http://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/news-analysis/luxury-market-growth-will-hit-low-point-in-2016-forecasts-bain |website=businessoffashion.com |accessdate=28 October 2016 |date=6 April 2016}}</ref> Asian-American sales associates at [[Macy's Herald Square]] sued [[Macy's]] for [[racial discrimination]] in September 2017, alleging that store managers instructed sales associates not to sell more than one unit to any single Asian customer, and that they were fired when they spoke up about the alleged discrimination.<ref> Kimberly Yam, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/macys-profiling-asian-shoppers-lawsuit_us_59c12e73e4b0186c2205dc2a Former Macy’s Employees Sue Company For Allegedly Racially Profiling Asian Shoppers] [[huffingtonpost.com]] 09/19/2017 </ref>
The daigou business is thriving in [[Australia]] and the government has also shown its support to recognize the job-creating potential of this grey industry.<ref name="auto"/>
