{{Expand Spanish|Roger Gougenot des Mousseaux|date=January 2012}}
[[File:Roger Gougenot des Mousseaux.png|thumb|upright=0.85|right|Roger Gougenot des Mousseaux.]]
'''Roger Gougenot des Mousseaux''' (1805–76) was a French writer and journalist. In 1860 he wrote ''La magie au dix-neufième siècle'', and in 1864 ''Les hauts phénomènes de la magie''.

An [[ultramontane]] antisemite, des Mosseaux's ''Le Juif, le judaïsme et la judaïsation des peuples chrétiens'' (1869) argued that Jews had manipulated the ideals of the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] to subvert and destroy Catholic France, and held them responsible for the [[French Revolution]].<ref>Rubenstein, Richard L., and John K. Roth. Approaches to Auschwitz: The Legacy of the Holocaust. London: SCM, 1987, p.74</ref> Gougenot des Mousseaux maintained that Jews engaged in ritual murder, conspired with [[Judeo-Masonic conspiracy theory|Freemasons]] to control the world, and that the French Revolution was wrong to grant them equal rights.<ref name="Michael">{{cite book |last1=Michael |first1=R. |title=A History of Catholic Antisemitism: The Dark Side of the Church |date=2008 |publisher=Springer |page=128}}</ref> [[Pope Pius IX]] blessed the work and Nazi ideologue [[Alfred Rosenberg]] edited and published the first German edition in 1921.<ref name="Michael" /> It was also heavily cited in [[Édouard Drumont]]'s popular anti-Semitic screed ''La France juive''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Socialism of Fools: Capitalism and Modern Anti-Semitism|last=Battini|first=Michele|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2016|isbn=|location=|page=48}}</ref>

